presentations.\n\n### 3.2 Agreement with a Proxy Reference\n\nTo complement the similarity score, we utilize proxy references generated by a high-quality ASR model, denoted as xproxysubscript𝑥proxyx\\_{\\text{proxy}}italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT proxy end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT. The comparison between the ASR-generated transcription xtextsubscript𝑥textx\\_{\\text{text}}italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT text end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT and the proxy reference xproxysubscript𝑥proxyx\\_{\\text{proxy}}italic\\_x start\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT proxy end\\_POSTSUBSCRIPT is quantified using Word Error Rate (pWER) and Character Error Rate (pCER) as defined in Appendix [A.1](https://arxiv.org/html/2502.12408v1#A1.SS1 \"A.1 Methodology ‣ Appendix A Appendix ‣ Potential Misuse and Bias. ‣ 8 Ethics Statement ‣ 7 Limitations ‣ 6 Conclusion ‣ Scaling Training Data for Regression. ‣ 5.3 Ablation ‣ 5 Results ‣ On the Robust Approximation of ASR Metrics\").\n\nThese metrics assess transcription quality by comparing it with a reliable proxy reference, without using ground-truth labels at any stage. Proxy references are dynamically selected by profiling 41 models across datasets and ranking them by average performance. For each target ASR model, the reference is the highest-ranking model other than the target itself. For example, if whisper-large-v3 ranks highest, the reference for whisper will be the second-best model. This ensures the proxy reference is both relevant and reliable for evaluating the target model.\n\n![Refer to caption](x1.png)\n\n### 3.3 Regression Model for Metric Prediction\n\nThe extracted features, including similarity scores and proxy metrics, are concatenated to form the input to a regression model. Let z=[Similarity,pWER/pCER]𝑧SimilaritypWERpCERz=[\\text{Similarity},\\text{pWER}/\\text{pCER}]italic\\_z = [ Similarity , pWER / pCER ] represent the feature vector. The regression model g𝑔gitalic\\_g estimates the ASR metrics y^^𝑦\\hat{y}over^ start\\_ARG italic\\_y end\\_ARG, denoted 